##VIEW SEQUENCES##

#import and view unaligned sequences
plantseqs <- readDNAStringSet("/Users/annawerkowski/Documents/plant.sequence.data.fasta", format = 'fasta')
#align sequences using MUSCLE parameters
read.plant.aln <- msaMuscle(plantseqs)
#save and export the alignment to use later
save.plant.aln <- msaConvert(read.plant.aln, type = "bios2mds::align")


#convert alignment to DNAbin object
plant.DNAbin <- as.DNAbin(read.plant.aln)
#identify base pair region of 16s rRNA gene to visualize
window <- plant.DNAbin[, 100:500]
#visualize sequence alignment
image.DNAbin(window, cex.lab = 0.50)

##LETS MAKE A PHYLOGENETIC TREE##

#create distance matrix with "raw" model
seq.dist.plant.raw <- dist.dna(plant.DNAbin, model = "raw", pairwise.deletion = FALSE)
#neighbor joining algorithm to construct tree
nj.plant.tree <- bionj(seq.dist.plant.raw)
#identify outgroup sequence
plant.outgroup <- match("MK526351.1 Pinus strobus ", nj.plant.tree$tip.label)
nj.plant.rooted <- root(nj.plant.tree, plant.outgroup, resolve.root = TRUE)

#plot the rooted tree
par(mar = c(1,1,2,1) + 0.1)
plot.phylo(nj.plant.rooted, main = "Neighbor Joining Tree", "phylogram",
           use.edge.length = FALSE, direction = "right", cex = 0.6,
           label.offset = 1)
add.scale.bar(cex = 0.7)

#create a distance matrix with "F84" model
seq.dist.plant.F84 <- dist.dna(plant.DNAbin, model = "F84", pairwise.deletion = FALSE)
#plot distances from different DNA substitution models
par(mar = c(5,5,2,1) + 0.1)
plot(seq.dist.plant.raw, seq.dist.plant.F84, pch = 20, col = "red", las = 1,
     asp = 1, xlim = c(0, 0.7), ylim = c(0, 0.7), xlab = "Raw Distance",
     ylab = "F84 Distance")
abline(b = 1, a = 0, lty = 2)
text(0.65, 0.6, "1:1")

##CREATE A COPHYLOGENETIC PLOT##

#make neighbor joining trees using different DNA substitution models
raw.plant.tree <- bionj(seq.dist.plant.raw)
F84.plant.tree <- bionj(seq.dist.plant.F84)
#define outgroups
raw.plant.outgroup <- match("MK526351.1 Pinus strobus ", raw.plant.tree$tip.label)
F84.plant.outgroup <- match("MK526351.1 Pinus strobus ", F84.plant.tree$tip.label)
#root the trees
raw.plant.rooted <- root(raw.plant.tree, raw.plant.outgroup, resolve.root = TRUE)
F84.plant.rooted <- root(F84.plant.tree, F84.plant.outgroup, resolve.root =TRUE)
#make a cophylogenetic plot
layout(matrix(c(1,2), 1, 2), width = c(1,1))
par(mar = c(1,1,2,0))
plot.phylo(raw.plant.rooted, type = "phylogram", direction = "right",
           show.tip.label = TRUE, use.edge.length = FALSE, adj = 0.5,
           cex = 0.6, label.offset = 2, main = "Raw")
par(mar = c(1,0,2,1))
plot.phylo(F84.plant.rooted, type = "phylogram", direction = "left",
           show.tip.label = TRUE, use.edge.length = FALSE, adj = 0.5,
           cex = 0.6, label.offset = 2, main = "F84")

##PHYLOGENETIC QUESTIONS## Based on the decisions above and the output, does your tree jibe with what is known about the evolutionary history of your organisms? If not, why? Is there anything you could do differently that would improve your tree, especially with regard to future analyses done by your team?

Based on what we know about these species, this tree makes a lot of sense. In addition, it makes sense that we would see these species growing together in a prairie habitat as they share similar evolutionary histories. This tree could be better if more of the species were included. We had nearly 60 species and including them all might generate some interesting information, but we are unsure as to exactly how helpful that would be right now. Seeing as the original data was not obtained to look at that sort of information, it makes sense that we wouldnt utilize it.
